<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Morella</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Rubus</i> <i>spectabilis</i> or <i>Sambucus</i> <i>racemosa</i> is dominant in the shrub layer with <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i>, <i>Frangula</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Holodiscus</i> <i>discolor</i>, <i>Lonicera</i> <i>involucrata</i>, <i>Ribes</i> <i>sanguineum</i>, <i>Rubus</i> <i>parviflorus</i>, <i>Rubus</i> <i>ursinus</i> and <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. The herbaceous layer is typically open including <i>Athyrium</i> <i>filix</i>-<i>femina</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>obnupta</i>, <i>Heracleum</i> <i>maximum</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>effusus</i>, <i>Polystichum</i> <i>munitum</i>, <i>Pteridium</i> <i>aquilinum</i>, <i>Scirpus</i> <i>microcarpus</i>, <i>Scrophularia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Stachys</i> <i>ajugoides</i> and <i>Urtica</i> <i>dioica</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Picea</i> <i>sitchensis</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i> ssp. <i>contorta</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Rubus spectabilis</i> > 50% relative cover in shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a).</li>
		
		<li><i>Rubus spectabilis, Morella californica, Lonicera involucrata, </i>and/or <i>Sambucus racemosa</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
		<li><i>Rubus spectabilis </i>or <i>Morella californica</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
		
		<li><i>Morella californica </i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a).</li>
		
		<li><i>Morella californica</i> or <i>Rubus spectabilis</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy on moist or wet soils (Buck-Diaz et al. 2020).</li>
		
		<li><i>Morella californica</i> or <i>Rubus spectabilis</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Wet swales, low drainages and gullies, edges of lakes, lagoons and sag ponds, moist to wet foggy slopes, along creeks and other riparian areas. Soils are loamy sand to clay loam derived from marine sediments. The USACE Wetland Inventory (2018 national list) recognizes <i>Rubus spectabilis</i> as a FAC plant, <i>Morella californica</i> as a FACW plant, and <i>Sambucus racemosa</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
