<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Rubus spectabilis </i>is 2-4 m high with upright stature, compound deciduous leaves, magenta flowers, and salmon-colored raspberry-like fruits. The leaves and bark have an astringent quality. Plants are an important nectar and food source for wildlife, and an important food source for Native Americans (Stevens and Darris 2000).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Morella californica </i>is 2-3 (10) m high with simple, thick, evergreen leaves that are fragrant. It has separate staminate flowers in catkins with showy, red stamens and nondescript pistillate flowers that form nutlike, wax-coated purplish fruits which are clustered amongst leaves along the branches.  The wax is used to make aromatic candles. Seedlings have low vigor. The species cannot survive exposure to temperatures below - 6 °C and has low tolerance to drought and restricted water conditions. Plants grow best in full sun but can tolerate light shade (Favorite 2005b). Older manuals use <i>Myrica californica </i>for this wax myrtle.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Sambucus racemosa </i>is a tall, shrub to 6 m tall in height, with deciduous compound leaves, white clusters of flowers, and bright red berries. Plants grow best in full sun but are shade tolerant. While it is a circumpolar species, it is occasionally dominant or co-dominant in moist areas. Plants are a nectar and food source for wildlife (Gonzalves and Darris 2016).<br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been updated since the 2009 edition of the Manual of California Vegetation, combining stands of <i>R. spectabilis</i> and <i>Morella californica,</i> along with <i>Sambucus racemosa,</i> and other tall shrubs. Stands of this alliance often form dense clonal thickets along moist swales, margins of wetlands, seeps, foggy slopes, low drainages, and other wetland/riparian sites usually within 1-2 km of the Pacific coast of California and possibly Oregon. Stands are typically small (<2 ha), occurring on moist to wet soils with high water tables in this foggy coastal strip of the coast (NatureServe 2014). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
